titlestmt.titleproper: Guide to the Collection of Bookplates by Edwin Davis French
titlestmt.author: Compiled by Nathaniel Dolquist

did.unittitle: Collection of bookplates by Edwin Davis French
did.abstract: This collection contains bookplates, original artwork, trial proofs, artist's proofs, additional process materials, and correspondence related to the production and/or exchange of bookplates by Edwin Davis French.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: The Yale Bookplate Collection was formerly housed in Sterling Memorial Library. The collection was incorporated into the Arts of the Book Collection in 1984 and then moved to the Seeley G. Mudd Library in 1990. In 2011, it was transferred to the Robert B. Haas Family Arts Library.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: The materials are open for research.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: Copyright has not been transferred to Yale University.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: Collection of Bookplates by Edwin Davis French, Robert B. Haas Family Arts Library, Yale University.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Some materials included in this collection indicate the provenance of the following bookplate collectors or collections: Joseph Manuel Andreini, Ada and William Fowler Hopson, Henry Rogers Winthrop, Warren Hiram Lowenhaupt, and others.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Edwin Davis French (1851-1906) was a designer and engraver born in North Attleboro, MA. In 1876 he moved to New York, NY, and he worked as a silver engraver and designer for Frank M. Whiting & Company until 1894. He also studied at the Art Students League. French became focused on copper engraving and designed his first bookplate in 1893. In 1897 he moved to Saranac Lake, NY, and he produced over 300 bookplate designs between 1893 and his death in 1906.
Reference: Brainerd, Ira Hutchinson. Edwin Davis French: A Memorial; His Life, His Art . New York: privately printed [De Vinne Press], 1908.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: E. D. French re-engraved the Jacobean bookplate of William Byrd of Virginia that was originally designed by Maverick. French's design was used by Francis Otway Byrd, George H. Byrd, Richard Evelyn Byrd, and William Byrd (of New York).

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Includes one signed print; note about the Candidati design by E. D. French.

This ex-libris design was used by members of a society of women writers, including the following individuals: Eveline Warner Brainerd, Helen Hunt Daly, Georgiana Goddard King, Kate Dickinson Sweetser, and Sarah King Wiley.
